1.4    Five-year Accident History

    The MPC Garyville Refinery has had only one release of a regulated substance in a covered process in the last five years, which resulted in an injury on-site.  This incident involved a release of a small amount of hydrogen fluoride (approximately 3 ounces) in the Alkylation Unit (Unit 27), which was contained on site.  On July 27, 2009 at 7:35 PM, hydrogen fluoride mixed with isobutane, butane and pump seal barrier fluid sprayed from a quick connect on the seal pot of the Main Fractionator Reflux Pump onto the operator's left arm and shoulder.  The operator was taken to the local hospital for treatment, remained overnight, and was released to go back to work the next day.  The weather conditions were as follows: the wind was at 10 miles per hour from the south west with the temperature at 85 degrees Fahrenheit and no precipitation.  The MPC Garyville Refinery notified the Louisiana State Police/Louisiana Department of Environmental Quality (LDEQ).  The pump was isolated and a plug installed to stop the leak.  The Garyville Refinery personnel were also reminded of the proper personal protective equipment to be worn while performing these types of tasks.  The property damage for Marathon has been set for $500,000, which was not exceeded as a result of this incident.  Additionally, no offsite impacts were associated with this incident.

